observations.recommendation:
We hereby recommended the following to the management:                  1.Make appropriate adjusting entries to recognize Property and Equipment for Distribution;
2. Expedite sub-dividing of the mother title with respect to the distribution of parcels of land to respective recipients;
3. Seek assistance with the Municipal Assessor to have the subdivided lands appraised; and
4. Advise the Municipal Accountant to coordinate regularly with the different focal persons on different projects to ensure correct and timely asset reclassification.

We hereby recommended the following to the management:                1. Adopt a stern policy and assert ownership of the said property;
2. Initiate a favorable contract of sale or usufruct with the trespassers;
3. Expedite the titling of the Land Property under TD No. 22-019-0013-00793;
4. Transfer the name of the tax declaration in favor of LGU San Fernando; and
5. Safeguard other land properties from illegal trespassers via fencing of the properties or other security measures

We hereby recommended the following to the management: 
1. Submit affidavit that the persons who have different signatures in the submitted Valid IDs and COEs are one and the same with the persons who signed the payroll sheets; 
2. Submit the acknowledgement receipts of the cash assistances of individual/s who failed to sign the payroll sheets;
3. Submit the Valid ID of the individual who lacked any proof of identification or submit a justification signed by the DSWD SWO to support the provision of assistance to the client regardless of the lack of Valid ID in line with DSWD MC No. 06 series of 2023;
4. Justify why various individuals were replaced; and
5. Ensure that succeeding initiatives should strictly review and verify the submitted documents prior to the release of any assistance

We recommended to the management the following actions:

 1) Write a collection letter to separated officials and re-establish payment terms of outstanding cash advances via a notarized agreement;
2) Prohibit the clearance of employees with pending accountabilities especially if the terminal leave benefits are not sufficient to cover the outstanding accountabilities or create a separate agreement or understanding between the LGU and the outgoing individual(s) to oblige them to pay the remaining balance of the cash advances net of terminal leave benefits even after their separation/clearance from the LGU;
 3) Ensure that cash advances are liquidated after their specific purposes are consummated; and
 4) Avoid the grant of additional cash advances if the official or employee still has a pending cash advance for liquidation.
5) Otherwise, if the outgoing individual/s refuse to pay their outstanding accountabilities, then the official/s who cleared him/her should shoulder the outstanding balance of cash advances of the separated employees as a consequence for their negligence.

We reiterated our recommendation to the Management to require:

a. The Chairman of the Inventory Committee, in coordination with the Municipal Engineer, to prepare and maintain an Inventory of all Local Roads and a road map. Likewise, ensure the preparation of the Report on the Physical Count of the Local Road Network (RPCLRN) at least annually;

b. The General Services Officer to prepare and maintain a Report on Local Road Network (RLRN) and keep a complete LRN Property Card for all roads and its component;

c. The Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the GSO with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects; and

d. The Municipal Accountant to provide depreciation for the remaining three (3) road networks and stop the provision of residual value for the depreciable components of the road network system. Moreover, if warranted, prepare adjusting entries duly supported with working papers and submit to the audit team to recognize changes in the provided depreciation.

We recommended to the Management to instruct the Municipal Accounting Office to:
a. Retrieve available records that will support the dormant liabilities totaling  ₱7,115,268.37 and analyze the propriety of the recording based on IPSAS 23.;
b. Review the records on the receipt and utilization of dormant balances from Provincial Government of Bukidnon totaling  ₱3,420,864.08 and make representation with the Provincial Government to determine the proper disposition of the excess funds.; 
c. Make necessary adjusting entries to transfer from trust fund to the general fund the dormant accounts totaling  ₱248,600.50 which should have been recorded as local income upon receipt.; and
d. Observe the guidelines provided under IPSAS 23 in recording revenue from non-exchange transactions.

We recommended that the LCE direct the:

City Treasurer’s Office, in coordination with the CAO, to regularly perform a detailed review and aging of all outstanding RPT and SEF receivables to determine which accounts have exceeded the five-year prescriptive period under Section 270 of the LGC;
Based on the aging analysis, CAO or any designated committee to recognize an allowance for doubtful accounts by estimating the portion of receivables that are unlikely to be collected by considering accounts that are now legally unenforceable due to the expiration of the prescriptive period and the history of voluntary payments of delinquent taxpayers. This evaluation should account for the age of the receivables, the presence or absence of collection actions, and any patterns of taxpayer compliance or non-payment over time;


City Treasurer to promptly issue demand letters or delinquency notices within a specified time after due dates, detailing amounts owed and consequences for non-payment, in order to strengthen collection procedures;


City Treasurer to implement administrative remedies such as levy or distraint, with all actions properly documented and notices served, if payments are not received within a specified time;


For high-value or persistent delinquencies, City Treasurer to formally recommend to the Legal Office the initiation of judicial proceedings, by identifying and reviewing substantial delinquent accounts and, where appropriate, instituting civil actions to enforce CGSFLU’s legal claims and facilitate the recovery of significant unpaid real property taxes;

We further recommended that CGSFLU establish and implement specific timeframes, as a matter of policy, for the actions outlined in recommendations (c) and (d), to ensure that collection measures are applied consistently and uniformly among all taxpayers. This approach will promote fairness, reinforce compliance, and support the timely enforcement of tax obligations.

We recommended that the LCE direct the:

CTO and CAO to jointly investigate and reconcile the discrepancies between the CIB-LCCA and Cashbook – CIB balances; 


CTO to ensure that financial data in the RCDs and RCIs are accurately recorded in the Cashbook – CIB;

CAO to properly record all financial data based on the submitted RCDs and RCIs;

CAO to prepare timely and accurate BRS and make necessary adjustments for any discrepancies; and

CTO and CAO to conduct reconciliations of the CIB-LCCA and Cashbook – CIB balances at least quarterly.

We recommended that the LCE direct the City Accountant to:

Provide JEVs and other necessary information to establish the nature of the identified adjustments;


Ensure that sufficient disclosures are provided for Prior Period Adjustments, detailing not only the affected accounts and their respective values but also the nature of the restatements, to enhance the reliability and transparency of the adjustments;


Establish policies strategically addressing issues and concerns on the record-keeping of transactions, ensuring availability and consistency of supporting documents, records, and reports; and


Explore the potential of the eNGAS by ensuring its full and proper utilization not only for the recording of financial transactions but also for the  efficient generation  of relevant financial information for the timely submission to the AT, in order to enhance the overall transparency, reliability and auditability of the CGSFLU’s financial reporting.

We recommended that the LCE direct the:

LSB to:

Enhance project planning and design processes to ensure that implementation modalities are properly identified and aligned with procurement laws and regulations. This includes clearly defining whether assistance will be provided in cash or in kind and ensuring that the appropriate method of implementation is reflected in the PPMP and SEF project proposals;

Revise the SEF disbursement process to prevent the use of authorization letters issued solely by the learners. SEF project proposals should include comprehensive and systematic procedures for the disbursement of financial assistance. This should account for the volume of participants and ensure that resources are available for efficient and accurate distribution;

Accountable Officers granted with cash advances to:

Require the submission of written consent or authorization from the parents or legal guardians of the learners who purportedly issued the authorization letters, in order to ratify and validate the otherwise voidable authorizations, in compliance with the provisions of the Civil Code of the Philippines on legal capacity;

Submit the following supporting documents:

Attendance sheets on projects involving financial assistance;
Monitoring report on the financial assistance to 3,037 learners for the 2024 NLC;
For the Brigada Eskwela
Proof of actual receipt of the financial assistance, and
Liquidation documents of the remaining ₱51,253.19

C. CAO to:

Establish a clear and strong system for monitoring and reviewing liquidation reports before they are recorded in the financial records. Ensure that all required documentation, such as receipts, official invoices, and supporting documents, are complete and submitted in a timely manner. Designate specific personnel responsible for conducting regular reviews to ensure compliance with the COA Circulars, and

Submit the JEV recording the liquidation and refund of Check No. 1811829.

We recommended that the LCE direct the CENRO to:

Inspect the dump trucks already procured by the recipient barangays and formulate strategies for modifying the trucks to ensure compliance with the requirements under the IRR of RA No. 9003;

Require the concerned barangays to execute a written undertaking or commitment to implement the recommended modifications, and monitor their compliance accordingly;

Discuss with Barangay Namtutan the deficiencies in their loan contract and cause the execution of an addendum incorporating the necessary provisions to address said deficiencies, and

Ensure that succeeding truck loan agreements with barangays include a specific timeline for procuring the garbage trucks, clear and defined specifications of the garbage trucks, and the equity required from the barangays to enable assessment of the effectiveness and efficiency of the program in promoting sustainable and legally compliant solid waste management for the CGSFLU.

We recommended that the LCE direct the City Agriculturist/ Veterinarian to:

Submit a list identifying the actual agricultural items received by the recipients;

Submit the monthly monitoring status report of the project as stated in the Monitoring and Evaluation item of the project proposal;

Ensure that all intended recipients of projects funded under RA No. 7171 are legitimate and duly registered farmers, with their names verified against official registration records prior to any distribution activity, and

Develop and adopt a standardized distribution protocol that includes, at a minimum, printed documentation of the recipient’s name, farmer’s ID number, type and quantity of inputs received, the corresponding project component, and the signatures, the distribution log properly reviewed and signed by authorized personnel.

We recommended that LCE direct the CAO to:

Investigate and resolve the unremitted balances, particularly those stemming from prior years. Identify the nature of each balance whether attributable to forwarding balances, unadjusted transactions, or erroneous deductions, and take corrective actions accordingly;

Establish and enforce a systematic and timely reconciliation process between payroll deductions and actual remittances to the GSIS, Pag-IBIG and PHIC. This should include monthly comparisons of amounts withheld versus amounts remitted and should be properly documented;

Maintain and regularly review detailed schedules of monthly payroll deductions and corresponding remittances to promptly identify and resolve discrepancies. Early detection will help prevent the accumulation of unremitted balances, which could otherwise complicate future reconciliation and monitoring efforts, and

Ensure that the NFS contain the required disclosures, including detailed breakdowns of the Due to GSIS and Due to Pag-IBIG accounts, such as premiums, loans, and MPL. This will enhance the transparency, accuracy, and completeness of CGSFLU’s financial reporting.

We have recommended that the Management:

Strictly adhere to the accounting and reporting guidelines on property management particularly Section 114 of the NGAS Manual. Prepare and maintain appropriate property cards and property ledger cards;

Properly fill-out the needed information in the physical inventory reports and property/ledger cards with substantial details for easy tagging and reconciliation;

Reconcile the records of PPE accounts between the Accounting Office and General Services Office and the RPCPPE, and adjust accordingly, and

Strengthen the function and responsibilities of the Physical Inventory Committee.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor and other concerned officials agreed to:
Submit the course/s of action for the unimplemented projects under the 20 per cent DF;
Ensure that allocations under the 20 per cent DF for CY 2024 and the years thereafter shall be covered with detailed project/program proposals in accordance with the procedural rules set forth in RA 7160 and DILG-DBM JMC No. 1 dated November 4, 2020.

We recommended and the Management agreed to:
Exert effort in locating the accountable officers with long overdue cash advances and issue demand letters for its liquidation especially to those who are still connected with the Municipality including the withholding of the accountable officers’ salary until the liquidation of the subject cash advances pursuant to Section 5.9 of COA Circular No. 97-002;
Assess the validity and collectability of each account for appropriate remedial action including the initiation of the procedures required under COA Circular 2023-008 for the write-off of the unsettled balances of the deceased accountable officers.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor and Municipal Treasurer agreed to institute proper controls in the custody and handling of the accountable forms by ensuring that:
Periodic reconciliation is conducted between quantities of the accountable forms on hand as against the reported in the CRAAF;
Provide a secure place for the accountable forms with clear order on the personnel with authorized access thereto;
Revisit the rules and procedures on the proper verification of the LO of the DSCAF of collectors ensuring its accuracy and completeness;
Prohibit the release of new accountable forms to AOs who failed to timely render complete and proper accounting of their accountabilities; and
Prohibit the transfer of accountable forms to unbonded and unauthorized personnel.

We recommended to the management to:
Require the MSWD to submit the lacking distribution sheets for the distributed welfare goods in CY 2024;
Require all departments/end-users to prepare RIS/Consumption reports when inventories are issued/consumed and submit them timely to the MGSO;
Instruct the MGSO to consolidate weekly the RIS, prepare SSMI reports, and submit to the Accounting Office;
Create an Inventory Committee that will conduct the semestral physical count of inventories, prepare and submit the RPCI to properly monitor the LGU's inventories; and,
Assess the book balances of inventories and institute adjustments, if warranted, duly supported with adequate documentations.

We recommended to management to do the following:
Ensure that the succeeding Projects/Programs/Activities report should contain all the relevant disclosures related to the project;
Adhere to the format presented in Annex 'B' of COA Circular 2013-004;
Deduct from the amount payable to the contractor the liquidated damages, the unrecouped balance of the advance payment, the withholding taxes, and any other legitimate claims of the LGU against the contractor;
Assess the merits of posting necessary accounting entries to record the liquidated damages and the unbilled portion of the accomplished works;
Justify the slow action of the management which led to the inadvertent waiver of the performance security;
Continue the contract termination procedures and submit copies of termination documents to the audit team;
Proceed for the blacklisting of the Contractor and deny succeeding involvement with the same contractor in future procurement activities;
Submit to COA the proof of execution of the blacklisting procedure against the contractor; and,
Ascertain that Bids and Awards Committee and the Municipal Engineer are steadfast in doing their duties at all times particularly, in evaluating the capacity and commitment of the contractor in handling any project, initiating termination and blacklisting procedure, if warranted.

We recommended management to submit the following:
Duly approved itinerary of actual travel approved by the Provincial Governor;
Quotation of three travel agencies or its equivalent for the plane fare;
Flight itinerary issued by the airline/ticketing office /travel agency;
Copy of the United Nations Development Program (UNDP) rate for DSA specific to country of destination, for the computation of the DSA being claimed;
Document to show the dollar to peso exchange rate at the date of travel;
Narrative report on trip undertaken/Report on Participation; and,
Paper/Electronic plane ticket, boarding passes, and terminal fee.
We further recommended that management should strictly adhere to the guidelines relating to foreign travel for all future out-of-country travels.

We recommended to the management to:
Submit the lacking documents to facilitate the completion of the audit;
Justify the variance noted in the land areas in the attached documents;
Expedite transfer of title in favor of the Municipal Government; and,
Strictly follow existing laws and guidelines for subsequent purchases of land and avoid paying the owner/s of the land before the documents are complete.

We recommended to the management to:
Submit the following documents:
Copy of appointment for new hires and the copies of resignation/retirement documents for CY 2024;
Certified list of members of RAFEUS as of September 30, 2024;
Certification stating that the employees and officials granted with CNA Incentives were not found guilty of any administrative and/or criminal cases;
Minutes of the union during the signing and ratification/referendum related to CNA; and,
Justification for non-withholding of taxes to 149 individuals.
Ensure that succeeding grants of CNA are properly substantiated and follow existing rules and regulations.
Ascertain that all disbursement transaction, including ADA transactions, are processed with disbursement vouchers that bear the proper approvals of all authorized officials.

We recommended the management to:
Justify the delays in the project implementation and variances of the construction materials;
Carefully plan projects considering meticulously the manpower complement, equipment utilization, and time allotment to avoid bottlenecks, work suspensions, and delays;
Create new inventory management strategies and implement the said strategies to improve inventory storage, utilization, and monitoring;
Assess management capacity in handling by administration projects and consider implementing projects by contract;
Advise the MEO to inspect the projects with un-updated project status;
Instruct the MEO to furnish certificates of completion to the accounting office after the inspection of completed projects, if any; and,
Diligently review and update the quarterly engineering reports in a timely manner and minimize/eliminate inaccuracies in preparing the reports.

We recommended the management to:
Adopt a stern policy and assert ownership of the said property;
Safeguard land properties from prospective illegal trespassers via fencing of the properties or other security measures;
Decide the intended use of the property and initiate favorable contracts of sale or usufruct with the trespassers if it intends to continue to allow them in the LGU land property. Otherwise, consider legal action to free the asset from unauthorized dwellers and allow government initiatives to be implemented on the asset; and,
Include these locals in future LGU relocation programs for households displaced by calamities, disasters, and similar events to promote the general welfare of the public and individuals.

We have recommended that the Management:

Strictly adhere to the accounting and reporting guidelines on property management particularly Section 114 of the NGAS Manual. Prepare and maintain appropriate property cards and property ledger cards;


Properly fill-out the needed information in the physical inventory reports and property/ledger cards with substantial details for easy tagging and reconciliation;


Reconcile the records of PPE accounts between the Accounting Office and General Services Office and the RPCPPE, and adjust accordingly, and

Strengthen the function and responsibilities of the Physical Inventory Committee.

We reiterated our recommendations that the LCE:
7) Prioritize issuance of demand letter to all accountable officers and employees to immediately liquidate/settle their outstanding CA;
8) Require the Municipal Accountant to immediately reconcile the Quarterly Monitoring of CA to the amounts reflected in the FS and strengthen the operation of preventive and monitoring controls to ensure timely submission of liquidation documents and avoid undue accumulation of outstanding CA;
9) Fast track the recovery of the documents relevant to the long outstanding CA and conduct verification, analysis and validation of them to determine their settlement/collectability and pursue collection, refund or liquidation, if warranted; and
10) Conform with the procedures and requirements set forth in COA Circular No. 2016-005 and immediately facilitate the request for write-off of dormant unliquidated CA.

We hereby recommended the following to the management:                  
1. Coordinate with the other key offices and secure the documents needed;
2. Have the donated lands appraised by the Municipal Assessor; 
3. Record necessary adjusting entries; and
4. Advise the Municipal Assessor, GSO and MPDO to furnish the accountant with proofs of donation every time the LGU receives donated properties to ensure accuracy of records.

We hereby recommended the following to the management:                  
1. Submit justification regarding the issues cited for further evaluation;
2. Submit the lacking documents requested as reflected in an indorsement dated January 16, 2024 including the As Built plan for the project;
3. Review the composition of the members of the BAC;
4. Ensure proper communication of departments involved in procurement activities;
5. Remind the BAC and other Heads of Offices that they should review the documents first prior to affixing their signature; and
6. Assess possibility of filing administrative action against responsible officials.

We hereby recommended the following to the management: 
1. Submit justification for the delays in the wage releases;
2. Create a more workable appointment processing scheme with clear lead times;
3. Convene with all the heads of offices and have them re-nominate different payrolls-in-charge to ensure timely submission of supporting documents, if the current point persons are not timely in their compliance;
4. Establish cut-off dates for DTRs and supporting documents submission; and
5. Issue a clear guideline/memorandum/internal policy to establish the process flow of the wage processing and release of the LGU is streamlined and made more efficient to ensure that release of the wages per cut-off period does not exceed the 16 days interval as set in the Labor Code.

We recommended to the management to do the following:

1. Create the SB ordinances fortifying the existence of their LEEs;
2. Ensure the preparation of Annual Operating Budgets for LEEs using its respective estimated/projected income relating to its operations; 
3. Stop charging Personal Services (PS) and Maintenance and Other Operating Expenses (MOOE) relating to the local economic enterprises against the General Fund Budgets;
4. Conduct a feasibility study and assess the sustainability of the Local Economic Enterprises; and
5. Maintain separate books for LEEs as noted in the NGAS Manual for transactions relating to the operations of the LEEs;
6. Otherwise, if in case the LGU determines that the LEEs are no longer feasible, we recommended that the LGU should absorb the enterprises, particularly the Public Market, Eco-Park, Public Market, Public Cemetery & the Terminal, in the general fund under a certain office/department as among its priority services and not as local economic enterprises under a separate office.

We recommended to the Management to require the-
a. General Services Officer to:
1. Prepare and submit the Report of the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) using the prescribed template;
2. Provide explanation on the discrepancy of P788,192.09 between Physical Inventory Report of the “Fuel, Oil and Lubricants” account and accounting records;
3. Maintain stock cards per for each commodity/stock and reconcile regularly with the supplies ledger cards from the Accounting Office and other property records like Acknowledgement Receipt for Equipment (ARE);
4. Submit regularly the SSMI to the Accountant and reconcile accordingly; and5. Coordinate in writing with the concerned Offices that are also custodians of inventories such as but not limited to the RHU/MHO and MDRRMO, to enable the timely preparation and submission of the SSMI or equivalent document to the Accounting Office.
b. Municipal Accounting Office to:
1. Require the submission of the SSMI and reconcile regularly with the GSO;
2. Maintain supplies ledger cards per for each commodity/stock; and3. Adopt the weighted average method for inventories carried on stock monthly.

We recommended that the LCE direct the City Accountant in coordination with the City Treasurer to:

Prepare and submit bank reconciliation statements for both LBP Account No. 0202-0028-97 (GF) and 0202-0258-11 (SEF), which were not submitted during CY 2022;



Ensure that the CY 2022 beginning and ending balances in the cashbook and cash in the local treasury ledger for both the General Fund (GF) and Special Education Fund (SEF) are reconciled;




If necessary, effect adjusting entries for the collections and deposits realized during CY 2022 which were unrecorded or erroneously recorded by either the City Accountant or the Treasurer; and  

Come up with strategies or mechanisms to further boost the cash control system

We recommended that the City Mayor direct the City Accountant to: 

Adjust the original and final budgets of the City in the amounts presented herein, in accordance with the authorized appropriations provided under its appropriation ordinances;

Prepare and maintain RAAOs in support of the SCBAA;




Cross-reference budgeted amounts against annual and supplemental budgets of the City enacted through appropriation ordinances in ascertaining the accuracy of the SCBAA; and

Reconcile the accounting records with the records of the Budget Office.

We reiterated our recommendations that the LCE require the (a) City Accountant to (i) consistently record the purchased inventories under the respective asset accounts; and

(ii) ensure that the de-recognition of inventories is recorded only when these are issued to end-users/beneficiaries; 

(b) City General Services (CGS) Officer to ensure proper safekeeping of supplies and materials inventory to minimize the risk of possible loss or wastage of government resources; 

and (c) CGS Officer and City Accountant to ensure coordination between their offices for the timely recording of receipts and issuances of inventories.

We recommended that Management 
(a) require the job-order personnel who failed to physically report to present themselves at the office of the Audit Team personally together with their valid IDs; 

(b) conduct sufficient intervention to address the continuous hiring of JOs such as lack of eligibility of those who have been continuously hired and rehired for years; 



(c) limit the assignment of essential duties in core offices to permanent and casual employees; 

(d) refrain from hiring JOs who will exercise supervisory control over regular employees; 

(e) refrain from hiring consultants whose functions are already being performed by the regular employees; and 

(f) strictly comply with the aforementioned CSC/COA/DBM Joint Memorandum Circular on the regularity of hiring JO employees.

We recommended  that the Local Chief Executive direct the 
(a)  Accountant and the  Treasurer to strictly comply with COA Circular No. 97-002 by ensuring that  payments are made in checks, except when it can be clearly shown that it is impossible, impractical or difficult to pay the suppliers by checks; 

(b)  Disbursing Officer to attach original copies of attendance sheet to avoid possible duplication in the usage thereof; 



(c) Accountable Officers concerned to provide adequate information to support claims for representation expenses as these facilitate verification and/or validation.  This can be in the form of a summary list which may contain the date, invoice/receipt number, name of the issuing establishment/party, the nature/particulars of the claims indicating the official purpose/s of the claims, the officials/parties/guests entertained, and the amount being reimbursed/claimed.

We reiterated our recommendation that Management require:
The Municipal Treasurer to maintain Stock Cards and Property Cards in accordance with Section 119 of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, Volume I;
The Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to reconcile the result of the actual physical count of PPE with the required PPE records to establish correctness and validity of the account balances presented in the financial statements;

Document the issuance of PPE to end-users through ARE to establish custodianship and assign accountability; 

Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare the lapsing schedule of all PPE to properly determine the correctness and validity of reported depreciation expenses and carrying value of PPE; and

Apply the One-Time Cleansing of PPE Account Balances under COA Circular No. 2020-006.

We recommended that Management be more prudent in the utilization of its LDRRMF, taking into consideration the existing rules and regulations governing the utilization of the said fund and require the:

MDRRMO to submit the Monthly Report on Sources and Utilization of the DRRMF duly certified correct by the Municipal Accountant on or before the 15th day after the end of each month;

MDRRMO and Municipal Budget Officer to allocate funds for the repair and maintenance of the DRRM tools and equipment chargeable against Maintenance and Other Operating Expenses of the MDRRM Office;

MDRRMO to properly classify the PPAs based on four thematic areas of disaster risk reduction and management and appropriately identify the funding source therefor in the LDRRMFIP in accordance with the guidelines provided under NDRRMC-DBM-DILG JMC No. 2013-1 dated March 25, 2013;

MDRRMO to incorporate in the LDRRMFIP and utilize the LDRRMF for tangible projects and activities that will help build disaster resilient communities and enhance disaster preparedness and response capabilities of the Municipality; and

Municipal Accountant to ensure that relief distribution sheets and other proof of distribution are attached to the DVs covering the purchase of relief goods for distribution for verification of this Office.

We reiterated our recommendation that Management:

Ensure that the PPAs for each year on SEF are implemented/utilized for the efficient and timely delivery of targeted services and benefits to the constituents in accordance with the proper utilization of the fund;

Prepare the SEF Budget in accordance with the prescribed format using Income and Expenditure Estimates Report during the preparation of SEF budget to provide a more accurate amount that must be appropriated for SEF;

Ensure that the prescribed planning and budgeting tools are effectively utilized to attain optimal and timely SEF budget; and

Strictly conform to the timelines in the planning and budgeting process as prescribed in DepEd-DBM-DILG JC No. 1, s. 2017.

We recommended that Management:

Strictly observe the pertinent provisions of RA No. 9184 and its applicable IRR, such that all procurements must be conducted through public bidding. Alternative methods of procurement must be resorted to only in highly exceptional cases provided for in RA No. 9184;

Require the BAC to supervise all types of procurement, not just infrastructure projects but also goods, pursuant to Section 11.1 of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184;

Discontinue procurement on a reimbursable basis unless extremely urgent, necessary and in small amount; and

Ensure that APP is properly accomplished in order to support the Annual Budget of the LGU, which must incorporate all its procurement requirements for each calendar year, to avoid audit disallowance thereof.

We recommended that:

Management require the AOs in the MTO to strictly comply with the timely remittance/deposit of their collections as provided in Section 32 Volume I of the Manual of the NGAS for LGUs. New stub of accountable forms must be issued to CCs only when collections from prior stubs issued to them were already remitted in full;

The AOs exercise diligence in the preparation of RCD and recording of transactions in the cashbook to avoid complexity and discrepancies with other records;

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE):
Direct the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to reconcile the difference of the Cash – Local Treasury account balance between their Offices, submit their working papers/reconciliation documents to the Office of the Auditor, and prepare necessary correcting entries in the Agency’s books or cashbooks;
Require the Municipal Treasurer to immediately deposit to the AGDB his undeposited collections and submit a copy of the deposit slip to the Office of the Auditor. Further, direct the Municipal Treasurer, the Liquidating Officer and the collectors to deposit/turnover all future collections intact and not to retain portion of them pursuant to the aforementioned provisions;
Review previous years’ reports, schedules and other documents to determine the specific accountabilities of the Former Municipal Treasurers who had undeposited collections; and
Strengthen internal control over collections, remittances and deposits to avoid retention of big amounts of money in the hands of the accountable officers.

We reiterated our recommendations that the LCE:
Prioritize issuance of demand letter to all accountable officers and employees to immediately liquidate/settle their outstanding CA;
Require the Municipal Accountant to immediately reconcile the Quarterly Monitoring of CA to the amounts reflected in the FS and strengthen the operation of preventive and monitoring controls to ensure timely submission of liquidation documents and avoid undue accumulation of outstanding CA;
Fast track the recovery of the documents relevant to the long outstanding CA and conduct verification, analysis and validation of them to determine their settlement/collectability and pursue collection, refund or liquidation, if warranted; and
Conform with the procedures and requirements set forth in COA Circular No. 2016-005 and immediately facilitate the request for write-off of dormant unliquidated CA.

We recommended that Management require the:
Municipal Accountant to observe due diligence in recording the transactions by using the appropriate accounts under COA Circular No. 2015-009 and following the series of proforma entries in taking up all transaction on RPT and SET. Likewise, make necessary correcting entries to rectify the noted errors;
Municipal Treasurer to furnish the Municipal Accountant of a duly certified list showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year in accordance with the above-mentioned guidelines stated under Section 20 of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the Inventory Committee to complete the conduct of inventory count of all the local roads and prepare and submit the RPCLRN;
Require the Municipal Engineer to provide the Inventory Committee with complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects to facilitate the preparation of RPCLRN;
Direct the Municipal Accountant and the GSO to prepare and maintain separate SLs/LRNLCs and LRNPCs, respectively, for local road projects and reconcile both records to ensure proper recording and control of the assets;
Require the GSO to prepare and submit the RLRN and Local Road Inventory and Road Map; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare a lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation for each component of road network and provide proper and complete disclosure of the total road networks in the Notes to FS in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2015-008.

We recommended that Management:
a. 	Explain the noted deficiencies in some of the submitted documents;
b. 	Ensure that a supplemental Local Development Investment Program (LDIP) and AIP be prepared to include the projects funded by the LGSF-SBDP NTF-ELCAC. Also, prepare and submit the Quarterly Report on Fund Utilization and Status of Program/Project Implementation using the prescribed format;
c. 	Require the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to review and undertake the proper examination of bidding documents and the conduct of procurement activities in accordance with the Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations (IRR) of RA No. 9184; and
d. 	Instruct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that the submitted disbursement vouchers are supported with complete and properly filled-out documentary requirements.

We recommended that the LCE, through the Municipal Solid Waste Management Board:
Hasten the revision process of the 10-year SWM Plan of the Municipality and submit immediately to NSWMC for approval;
Strictly enforce and intensify the information campaign on “no segregation, no collection” policy among residents and consider imposing fines and penalties for violators thereof;
