We reiterated our recommendations in our previous audit observation that the Municipal Mayor:

a. direct the inventory team to conduct the physical count of all its PPE, and thereafter immediately cause the submission of the Report of Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment as of December 31,2015;

b. direct the Agency Accountant to cause the immediate updating and preparation of individual subsidiary ledgers for each PPE account to facilitate periodic reconciliation and proper monitoring of said accounts;

c. augment the workforce in the Accounting Section where the bulk of the various transactions of the Municipality are being processed, recorded and reported by hiring additional staff to work on the updating, reconciliation and subsequent monitoring and maintenance of the records for the PPE accounts at the soonest time possible; and

d. to facilitate physical inventory and immediate reconciliation with records, employ additional manpower to conduct the inventory taking on a full-time basis.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer:

a. to revisit the status of the outstanding checks of the LGU to determine whether they are still in the custody of the cashier or in the hands of the payees;

b. if checks were already issued, determine whether they are subject for replacement or not;

c. effect/record in the books the necessary adjustments, as provided for under Section 59 of the NGAs to ensure accuracy of the cash balance appearing in the LGU’s financial reports;

d. that checks, when not claimed remain in the custody of the Municipal Treasurer and be detached from the original voucher, to facilitate determination of unclaimed vouchers at year-end;

e. to file photocopies of the vouchers with the individual check for easy reference; and

f. to verify the state of additional stale checks for the year to determine the correctness of its set-up in books and to make necessary adjustments correspondingly.
